_:r1b5 <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P190_has_symbolic_content> "The Auction as Artwork" .
_:r1b5 <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P2_has_type> <http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300404670> .
_:r1b5 <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P72_has_language> <http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300388277> .
_:r1b5 <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E33_E41_Linguistic_Appellation> .
_:r1b6 <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P190_has_symbolic_content> "work:auction-as-artwork" .
_:r1b6 <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P2_has_type> <http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300312355> .
_:r1b6 <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E42_Identifier> .
_:r1b7 <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P190_has_symbolic_content> "The primary Metaconceptual Art work of March 30, 2009: the act of the Sotheby's Photographs auction itself, designated as the artwork. Following the logic of the readymade, Sun & Rain Works appropriates a public institutional event — the auction carried out by Sotheby's — and frames its mechanism of value, authority, and sale as the material of the work. Two artifacts are parts of this single gesture: the born-digital website www.wtfisart.com and the auction performance work WTF is Ansel Adams." .
_:r1b7 <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P2_has_type> <http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300435416> .
_:r1b7 <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E33_Linguistic_Object> .
_:r1b8 <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P190_has_symbolic_content> "Sun & Rain Works reports that photographs, metadata, emails, auction catalogue material, receipts, and related records document the work. The public Linked Art record names the work, the appropriated auction, and its parts; the fuller evidence archive remains held by the studio pending redaction and rights review." .
_:r1b8 <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P2_has_type> <http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300435416> .
_:r1b8 <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E33_Linguistic_Object> .
